.SH Description
\f[CR]SHMultiTaperSE\f[R] will perform a localized multitaper spectral
analysis of an input function expressed in spherical harmonics.
The maximum degree of the localized multitaper cross\-power spectrum
estimate is \f[CR]lmax\-lmaxt\f[R].
The coefficients and angular orders of the windowing coefficients
(\f[CR]tapers\f[R] and \f[CR]taper_order\f[R]) are obtained by a call to
\f[CR]SHReturnTapers\f[R].
If \f[CR]lat\f[R] and \f[CR]lon\f[R] or \f[CR]alpha\f[R] is specified,
the symmetry axis of the localizing windows will be rotated to these
coordinates.
Otherwise, the localized spectral analysis will be centered over the
north pole.
.PP
If the optional array \f[CR]taper_wt\f[R] is specified, these weights
will be used in calculating a weighted average of the individual
\f[CR]k\f[R] tapered estimates \f[CR]mtse\f[R] and the corresponding
standard error of the estimates \f[CR]sd\f[R].
If not present, the weights will all be assumed to be equal.
When \f[CR]taper_wt\f[R] is not specified, the mutltitaper spectral
estimate for a given degree will be calculated as the average obtained
from the \f[CR]k\f[R] individual tapered estimates.
The standard error of the multitaper estimate at degree \f[CR]l\f[R] is
simply the population standard deviation,
\f[CR]S = sqrt(sum (Si \- mtse)\(ha2 / (k\-1))\f[R], divided by
\f[CR]sqrt(k)\f[R].
See Wieczorek and Simons (2007) for the relevant expressions when
weighted estimates are used.
.PP
The employed spherical harmonic normalization and Condon\-Shortley phase
convention can be set by the optional arguments \f[CR]norm\f[R] and
\f[CR]csphase\f[R]; if not set, the default is to use geodesy 4\-pi
normalized harmonics that exclude the Condon\-Shortley phase of
(\-1)\(ham.
.SH References
Wieczorek, M. A. and F. J. Simons, Minimum\-variance multitaper spectral
estimation on the sphere, J. Fourier Anal.
Appl., 13, doi:10.1007/s00041\-006\-6904\-1, 665\-692, 2007.
